Machine Learning with R.

Real estate market Switzerland in 2018.

Tomasz Bielaczyc



Our goal is to see how the features like location, number of rooms or date of built can be used
to predict the price of house or apartment. We will compare a couple of machine learning tools.

1. From raw to useful data.

We have three files of data downloaded using Web Scraper from home.ch.

be <- read_csv("bern_home.csv")                               #library(tidyverse)
gr <- read_csv("graubuenden_home.csv")
zh <- read_csv("zurich_home.csv")

We add the information about canton (which will be useful for visualization). Then we join three sets of data.

be$canton <- "BE"; gr$canton <- "GR"; zh$canton <- "ZH"

BEGRZH <- (zh %>% full_join(gr)) %>% full_join(be)

glimpse(BEGRZH)                                               #Let's take a quit look at the data.

Our data are a bit messy. We have to prepare them for further use.

BEGRZH <- BEGRZH %>%
  select(category:canton) %>%                                 #We don't need some columns
  rename(year = `year built`, space = `living space`)         #and we don't want two-word col-names.

BEGRZH <- BEGRZH %>% 
  mutate(year = as.numeric(year)) %>%                         #We want "year" to be a number,
  filter(!is.na(year))                                        #we remove NA created in this way.

BEGRZH <- BEGRZH %>% 
  mutate(rooms = as.numeric(rooms)) %>%                       #We do the same with "rooms".
  filter(!is.na(rooms))

BEGRZH <- BEGRZH %>% 
  filter(str_detect(space, "m2$")) %>%                        #Remove "m2" from end of "space".
  mutate(space = as.numeric(str_replace(space, " m2", "")))

BEGRZH <- BEGRZH %>%                        
  filter(!str_detect(price, "^P")) %>%                        #Remove rows with 'Price for request'
  mutate(price = as.numeric(str_replace_all(price, "'", ""))) #and adjust formatting of numbers.

2. Data visualisation

We can visualize our data in many different ways.

Price / size, canton.

Of course the price depends on the size of the flat. Let’s have a look.

BEGRZH %>% 
  ggplot(aes(space, price, color = canton)) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(50, 400), 
                  ylim = c(0, 4e+06)) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(face = "bold", color = "blue"),
        axis.text.y = element_text(face = "bold", color = "blue")) +
  labs(title = "Zurich, Bern and Graubuenden regions apartments", 
           x = "Living space",
           y = "Price") +
  geom_point()

Price / rooms, category.

Similarly prices depend of the number of rooms. By the way let’s see the differences among different categories.

ggplot(data = BEGRZH) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = rooms, y = price)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ category, nrow = 2)

Mean prices

Let’s draw mean price in every category. Let’s also see if the prices strongly depend of the decade of built.

cat_price <- BEGRZH %>%
  group_by(category) %>%
  transmute(av_pr = mean(price))

plot_cat_price <-
  ggplot(BEGRZH, aes(x = category)) + 
  geom_point(aes(y = price)) +
  geom_point(data = cat_price, aes(y = av_pr), colour = "red", size = 3) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

dec_price <- BEGRZH %>% 
  mutate(decade = cut(year, breaks = seq(from = 1945, to = 2025, by = 10))) %>%
  group_by(decade) %>%
  summarise(av_pr = mean(price))

plot_dec_price <-
  ((BEGRZH %>% mutate(decade = cut(year, breaks = seq(from = 1945, to = 2025, by = 10)))) %>%
  full_join(dec_price, by = "decade")) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = decade)) + 
  geom_point(aes(y = price)) +
  geom_point(aes(y = av_pr), colour = "red", size = 3) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))

grid.arrange(plot_cat_price, plot_dec_price, ncol=2)

Map

Let’s see the location of the apartments on the map.

ch_postal <- read_csv("ch_postal_codes.csv")
ch_postal <- ch_postal %>%                                    #Add Latitude 
  select(`Postal Code`, Latitude, Longitude)                  #and Longitude to the table.
                    
BEGRZH <- BEGRZH %>%        
  left_join(ch_postal, c("where" = "Postal Code"))

leaflet(BEGRZH) %>%                                           #Use openstreetmap.
  addTiles() %>%
  addMarkers(lng = ~Longitude, 
             lat = ~Latitude, 
             label = ~as.character(where),
             clusterOptions = markerClusterOptions()
             )

…we define a function that compares errors.

AvErr <- function(act, pred) {
  mean(abs(act - pred))
  }

The average difference between the average price and the actual price is over 40%. It’s worth to look for a better approximation of prices than the average price.

BEGRZH_test_av = mean(BEGRZH_test$price)
BEGRZH_test_av; AvErr(BEGRZH_test$price, BEGRZH_test_av)    
## [1] 989000
## [1] 421633.3


a) Linear regression

Let’s start with something basic.

BEGRZH_price_Regr <- lm(price ~ ., data = BEGRZH_train)

We can see how this tool coped with non-numeric data (dividing them into parts). The p-value is small, so the model is in small extent accidental. The R-squared says that model explains the price value in about fifty percent.
Let’s apply this model for the test data…

BEGRZH_test_Regr <- predict(BEGRZH_price_Regr, BEGRZH_test)

…and see the correlation between predicted and real price and the average error.

cor(BEGRZH_test$price, BEGRZH_test_Regr)                    
## [1] 0.7345268
AvErr(BEGRZH_test$price, BEGRZH_test_Regr)                  
## [1] 273977.7


b) Support Vector Machines

This very nice mathematical concept relies on finding hyperplanes that distinctly classify the data points.

BEGRZH_price_SVM <- ksvm(price ~ ., data = BEGRZH_train)      #library(kernlab)
BEGRZH_test_SVM <- predict(BEGRZH_price_SVM, BEGRZH_test)

cor(BEGRZH_test$price, BEGRZH_test_SVM)
##          [,1]
## [1,] 0.795718
AvErr(BEGRZH_test$price, BEGRZH_test_SVM)
## [1] 220951.5

Of course SVM gave us a better result then regression algorithm.


c) Random Forest

The name is quite appropriate: we take a bunch of decision trees to create the forest.

BEGRZH_price_RF <- randomForest(price ~ .,
                                data = BEGRZH_train, 
                                ntree = 50, 
                                mtry = 5)                     #library(randomForest)
BEGRZH_test_RF <- predict(BEGRZH_price_RF, BEGRZH_test)

cor(BEGRZH_test$price, BEGRZH_test_RF)
## [1] 0.8547799
AvErr(BEGRZH_test$price, BEGRZH_test_RF)
## [1] 192799.6

We’ve grown 50 trees drew five predictors for each. Increase of those numbers wouldn’t change the outcome too much.

Ultimately We obtained about 10% error and it seems doubtful that we could improve the result significantly. Especialy, after taking a look at the individual results of models applications, we can see that some exemples just do not fit in the scheme.

t <- tibble("True price" = BEGRZH_test$price,
            "Average price" = BEGRZH_test_av,

4. Principal Component Analysis

Let’s try to reduce the number of features.

Manual approach

First we just look at the features and decide which are the least useful. Since Latitude and Longitude give us the exact locations it seems reasonable to omit “where” and “canton”. I’m also just guessing that the category is not that important.

BEGRZH_price_RF2 <- randomForest(price ~ .,
                                data = BEGRZH_train[, -c(1, 3, 7)], 
                                ntree = 50, 
                                mtry = 5)
BEGRZH_test_RF2 <- predict(BEGRZH_price_RF2, BEGRZH_test[, -c(1, 3, 7)])

str(BEGRZH_train[, -c(1, 3, 7)])

PCA

Using the after-PCA data

We create BEGRZH_PCA_train and BEGRZH_PCA_test using the same transformation.

BEGRZH_PCA_train <- as.data.frame(BEGRZH_PCA$x)
BEGRZH_PCA_test <- as.data.frame(predict(BEGRZH_PCA, newdata = BEGRZH_n_test))

BEGRZH_PCA_train <-  data.frame(price = BEGRZH_n_train[ , 10], BEGRZH_PCA_train)
BEGRZH_PCA_test <-  data.frame(price = BEGRZH_n_test[ , 10], BEGRZH_PCA_test)

Let’s try random forest for all the new data.

BEGRZH_price_RF3 <- randomForest(price ~ ., 
                                 data = BEGRZH_PCA_train, 
                                 ntree = 50, 
                                 mtry = 5)
BEGRZH_test_RF3_Pred <- predict(BEGRZH_price_RF3, BEGRZH_PCA_test)

cor(BEGRZH_test_RF3_Pred, BEGRZH_PCA_test$price); AvErr(BEGRZH_test_RF3_Pred, BEGRZH_PCA_test$price)
## [1] 0.7976449
## [1] 232284.8

We can see that our transformation already made it worse. Now, let’s figure out how much data we should consider.

BEGRZH_PCA$sdev                                               #standard deviation of every component
##  [1] 1.804801410091772861932 1.796877017446439239734 1.507935447689756403022 1.095723827699184749207

BEGRZH_PCA_train_var <- (BEGRZH_PCA$sdev)^2

     xlab = "Principal Component",

We can see that starting from the ninth feature, they do not vary too much. Hence they don’t give too much information.

plot(cumsum(BEGRZH_PCA_prop_var), xlab = "Principal Component",
     ylab = "Cumulative Proportion of Variance",
     type = "b")                                              #cumulative scree plot

Let’s get rid of the last six. PCA is a great tool when we have a lot of features (and we don’t fully understand them), but apparently it’s not always useful.

BEGRZH_price_RF4 <- randomForest(price ~ .,

We have nine features and the result is much worse then with manually chosen six.

5. Category predictions - classyfication models

Our last goal is to recognize if the category is “Apartment” or not.

BEGRZH_train <- BEGRZH_train %>% 
  mutate(category = ifelse(category == "Apartment", 1, 0))
BEGRZH_test <- BEGRZH_test %>% 
  mutate(category = ifelse(category == "Apartment", 1, 0))


a) Logical Regression

Once again we start with regression.

BEGRZH_cat_Regr <- glm(category ~ ., data = BEGRZH_train)
BEGRZH_test_Regr <- predict(BEGRZH_cat_Regr, BEGRZH_test)
BEGRZH_test_Regr <- ifelse(BEGRZH_test_Regr > .5, 1, 0)

table(BEGRZH_test$category, BEGRZH_test_Regr, dnn = c('Real', 'Regr-Predicted'))
##     Regr-Predicted
## Real   0   1
##    0  61  42
##    1  15 182

Let’s see how big is the percentige of correct guesses.

100 * sum(BEGRZH_test$category == BEGRZH_test_Regr) / length(BEGRZH_test_Regr)
## [1] 81


b) Support Vector Machines

If we change “category” to factors the ksvm-functions will recognize that we want classification instead of regression.

BEGRZH_train$category <- as.factor(BEGRZH_train$category)
BEGRZH_test$category <- as.factor(BEGRZH_test$category)

BEGRZH_cat_SVM <- ksvm(category ~ ., data = BEGRZH_train, kernel = "vanilladot")
##  Setting default kernel parameters
BEGRZH_test_SVM <- predict(BEGRZH_cat_SVM, BEGRZH_test)

table(BEGRZH_test$category, BEGRZH_test_SVM, dnn = c('Real', 'SVM-Predicted'))
##     SVM-Predicted
## Real   0   1
##    0  64  39
##    1  17 180
100 * sum(BEGRZH_test$category == BEGRZH_test_SVM) / length(BEGRZH_test_SVM)
## [1] 81.33333

e) Nearest Neighbours

Here we will need normalized numerical data.

normalize <- function(x){
  return ((x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x)))
  }
BEGRZH_n <- BEGRZH_n %>% select(year:Longitude)
BEGRZH_n <- as.data.frame(lapply(BEGRZH_n, normalize))

BEGRZH_n_train <- BEGRZH_n[samp, ] 
BEGRZH_n_test <- BEGRZH_n[-samp, ]

BEGRZH_test_kNN <- knn(train = BEGRZH_n_train,
                      test = BEGRZH_n_test,
                      cl = BEGRZH_train$category,
                      k = 25)                                 #library(kernlab)

table(BEGRZH_test$category, BEGRZH_test_kNN, dnn = c('Real', 'RF-Predicted'))
##     RF-Predicted
## Real   0   1
##    0  57  46
##    1  11 186
round(100 * sum(BEGRZH_test$category == BEGRZH_test_kNN) / length(BEGRZH_test_kNN), 3)
## [1] 81

We can see that though we used very simple model, the answer is very similar to those obtained by much more complicated algorithms.

f) Neuron Nets

For this model we will also need normalized data.

BEGRZH_n_train$category <- (as.numeric(levels(BEGRZH_train$category)[BEGRZH_train$category]))

BEGRZH_test_NN  <- neuralnet(category ~ year + where + rooms + space + price +
                             cantonBE + cantonGR + cantonZH + Latitude + Longitude,
                             data = BEGRZH_n_train, hidden = 2) #library(neuralnet)
plot(BEGRZH_test_NN, rep = "best")

BEGRZH_test_NN <- compute(BEGRZH_test_NN, BEGRZH_n_test)
BEGRZH_test_NN <- BEGRZH_test_NN$net.result
BEGRZH_test_NN <- ifelse(BEGRZH_test_NN > .5, 1, 0)

table(BEGRZH_test$category, BEGRZH_test_NN, dnn = c('Real', 'RF-Predicted'))
##     RF-Predicted
## Real   0   1
##    0  63  40
##    1  18 179
round(100 * sum(BEGRZH_test$category == BEGRZH_test_NN) / length(BEGRZH_test_kNN), 3)
## [1] 80.667
